{#
  nginx realip snippet for the cinny pod, mounted (subPath) into conf.d/ and thus
  included inside the image's http{} block. The stock nginx.conf and default.conf
  stay untouched.

  Why: without realip, $remote_addr is the Traefik POD ip, so every access-log line
  reads 10.68.x.y and the real client only appears in the trailing
  $http_x_forwarded_for field of the default "main" log_format. realip rewrites
  $remote_addr itself, so ALL log lines become correct.

  Why BOTH hops are trusted: nginx walks the XFF chain right-to-left
  (real_ip_recursive) and stops at the first UNtrusted entry. Trusting only the pod
  CIDR would stop at the edge ip and report that. Trusting the edge too lets it walk
  one more step, to the actual client.
  Chain: <client> -> nginx edge -> HAProxy -> Traefik pod -> cinny.

  This lives in a .j2 rather than inline in the task: a column-0 {% %} tag inside a
  ConfigMap data block breaks the YAML parse, and the inline join workarounds hit
  Jinja/YAML escaping (a '\n' separator rendered as a literal backslash-n, and a
  regex_replace '\1' backreference rendered literally). In a template file neither
  problem exists.

  cluster_cidr leads the list so it is never empty: a bare "set_real_ip_from ;" is a
  config error, and that is what a clone without the vault (dummy = []) would render.

  NOTE: real client ips only appear once Traefik forwards them, i.e. with
  traefik_forwarded_trusted_ips live on the websecure entrypoint. Without it Traefik
  overwrites XFF with the edge ip and the walk ends there: same output as before,
  never worse.
#}
# First entry = Traefik pods (this nginx's direct peer), rest = upstream proxies.
{% for ip in [cluster_cidr] + (traefik_forwarded_trusted_ips | default([])) %}
set_real_ip_from {{ ip }};
{% endfor %}
real_ip_header X-Forwarded-For;
real_ip_recursive on;
